### 4. Government Initiatives and Programs

#### 4.1 Clean Power Plan and Greenhouse Gas Regulations (U.S. EPA)

- **Overview:**  
  The EPA’s Clean Power Plan aimed to reduce carbon dioxide emissions from power plants by 32% below 2005 levels by 2030.  
- **State Plans:**  
  States were required to submit compliance plans, with options for individual or multi-state approaches, including market-based trading programs.  
- **Legislative and Legal Challenges:**  
  Many states enacted legislation for legislative review of plans or delayed implementation pending legal rulings.  
- **Economic and Environmental Benefits:**  
  Expected to reduce greenhouse gases, improve public health, and save consumers money through improved fuel efficiency ([EPA Greenhouse Gas Emission Limits](https://www.ncsl.org/research/energy/epa-greenhouse-gas-emission-limits-what-they-mean-for-state-legislatures.aspx)).

#### 4.2 Fuel Economy Standards

- **EPA’s 2021 Rule:**  
  New fuel economy standards require cars and light trucks to improve fuel efficiency by 5-10% annually from 2023 to 2026, targeting 40 miles per gallon by 2026.  
- **Benefits:**  
  Reduction in carbon emissions, improved air quality, and cost savings for consumers.  
- **Criticism:**  
  Some environmental groups argue standards are not stringent enough to meet long-term climate goals ([NPR](https://www.npr.org/2021/12/20/1066489707/epa-announces-tighter-fuel-economy-standards-for-cars-and-trucks)).

