### 5. Waste Management and Circular Economy Policies

Effective waste management is crucial for reducing pollution and conserving resources.

#### 5.1 Challenges  
- Complexity and fragmentation of recycling systems.  
- Contamination of recyclables reduces efficiency.  
- Plastic pollution crisis, with only 8% of U.S. plastic waste recycled.  
- Impact of China's National Sword policy restricting waste imports, disrupting global recycling markets.  
- COVID-19 pandemic exacerbated operational challenges ([National League of Cities](https://www.nlc.org/resource/beyond-recycling-policy-to-achieve-circular-waste-management/)).

#### 5.2 Principles for Reform  
- **Embrace Circular Economy:**  
  Designing systems where waste is minimized and materials are reused or recycled continuously.  
- **Maintain Local Authority:**  
  Local governments are best positioned to manage waste collection and respond to community needs.  

#### 5.3 Government Actions  
- Develop comprehensive circular waste management plans.  
- Equal priority for trash, recycling, and organic waste collection.  
- Adopt environmentally preferential procurement (EPP) standards to spur market demand for recycled products.  
- Support local businesses in adopting circular economy practices.  
- Set clear standards for worker safety and equity in waste management services.  
- Implement Extended Producer Responsibility (EPR) to hold manufacturers accountable for product lifecycle impacts.  
- Establish minimum recycled content mandates to stimulate demand for recycled materials.  
- Create standardized labeling and recyclability guidelines to reduce consumer confusion ([National League of Cities](https://www.nlc.org/resource/beyond-recycling-policy-to-achieve-circular-waste-management/)).

